  "answer": "**No such verse appears in Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 3.**\n\nChapter 3 covers expiation (*prāyaścittādhyāya*), including ritual impurity from birth/death (verses 1–34), duties in distress (35–44, permitting a distressed Brāhmaṇa to eat food from any source without sin[^1]), hermit duties (45–55), ascetic duties (56ff.), and metaphysics/anatomy. A student after a teacher's death should avoid food from restricted sources,[^2] but no penance—let alone for *swallowing* forbidden food—is prescribed. Corpus-wide searches for related terms (e.g., \"penance food forbidden,\" \"swallowing food\") yielded no matches here or elsewhere fitting the description.\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-c03f6a](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-c03f6a).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-c7b7b1](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-c7b7b1).",
